Chapter 2 – Part 5: Creating Multiple Pages and Navigation

Now our application has:
• Two templates
• Two routes
• Links between pages

This is how real websites work.

Project Structure Now
learnFlaskApp/
├── __init__.py
├── routes.py
└── templates/
    ├── index.html
    └── newPage.html

Updated routes.py
      from learnFlaskApp import app
      from flask import render_template
      
      @app.route('/')
      @app.route('/index/<int:count>')
      def index(count=0):
          info = { 'heading': 'This is Flask index page' }
          return render_template(
              'index.html',
              other='This is a kind of paragraph',
              info=info,
              count=count
          )
      
      @app.route('/profile')
      def profileRoute():
          info = { 'heading': 'This is Profile page' }
          return render_template(
              'newPage.html',
              other='Welcome to the new page!',
              info=info
          )

index.html
      <!DOCTYPE html>
      <html>
      <head>
          <title>Flask Page</title>
      </head>
      <body>
          <a href="/profile">New Page</a>
          <hr>
          <h1>{{ info.heading }}</h1>
          <p>{{ other }}</p>
          <hr>
          <p>{{ count }}</p>
      </body>
      </html>

newPage.html
      <!DOCTYPE html>
      <html>
      <head>
          <title>Flask Page</title>
      </head>
      <body>
          <a href="/">Index</a>
          <hr>
          <h1>{{ info.heading }}</h1>
          <p>{{ other }}</p>
          <hr>
          <p>{{ count }}</p>
      </body>
      </html>

What Is Happening Now?
Two Different URLs
URL	Function	Template
/	index()   index.html
/profile    profileRoute()	newPage.html

Each route renders a different HTML page.

Navigation Between Pages
Inside index.html:
      <a href="/profile">New Page</a>

Clicking this link:
Sends request to /profile
Calls profileRoute()
Renders newPage.html
Inside newPage.html:
      <a href="/">Index</a>

Clicking this link:
Sends request to /
Calls index()
Renders index.html
This is basic page navigation.

Full Execution Flow
User starts at:
      http://127.0.0.1:5000/
Click “New Page”
Browser → /profile
        ↓
profileRoute()
        ↓
render_template('newPage.html')
        ↓
HTML returned

Click “Index”
Browser → /
        ↓
index()
        ↓
render_template('index.html')

Important Observation
In newPage.html, we have:
      <p>{{ count }}</p>

But in profileRoute() we are NOT sending count.
So:
      return render_template(
          'newPage.html',
          other='Welcome to the new page!',
          info=info
      )

There is no count variable here.
Flask will render count as empty.

Best Practice Fix
Either:
Option 1 — Remove count from newPage.html
OR
Option 2 — Send a default value:
      return render_template(
          'newPage.html',
          other='Welcome to the new page!',
          info=info,
          count=0
      )

Important Concept Learned Here
We now understand:
• Multiple routes
• Multiple templates
• Page navigation
• Data passing
• Dynamic routes
• Default parameters

This is already the foundation of real applications.

Improvement (Very Important)
Instead of hardcoding:
      <a href="/profile">
We should use:
      <a href="{{ url_for('profileRoute') }}">
Why?
Because if we change the route later, links won’t break.

This is professional Flask style.

Mental Model
Route → Function → Template → Link → Another Route

